John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
The Scottish independent schools have traditionally provided excellent education. In view of the new outstanding exam results, this situation has not changed since 2018, which is further enhanced by individual and group success in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
In Scotland, more than 30 000 students are already studying in such institutions, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which strive to provide students and parents with the best possible services.
Independent schools strive to prepare students for further education, higher education, their chosen careers and their position as world citizens.
In an educational sector where it is possible to design and introduce tailor-made school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and sought after subjects.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to someone in a language that he understands, it reaches his head.
But if you speak his language, it will reach his heart."
This is an important reminder because we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year's exam results show that students from independent schools across the country have produced the best results in foreign languages.
68 percent of all students studying foreign languages reached a higher A (more than 85 percent).
Based on the data collected from SCIS 74 member schools, 72 percent of students received a higher grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students in German, 69 percent French and 63 percent of Spanish reached A.
These results also support the fact that independent schools in Scotland view foreign languages as essential knowledge, which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today languages, as chosen objects, have become as important as science, technology, engineering and mathematics, both in independent and other schools.
The 2014 UK Employment and Vocational Training Committee survey showed that 17 percent of employers say that filling empty positions is difficult due to a lack of language skills.
This also shows that language skills are becoming more and more necessary for young people to have a successful career.
As the knowledge of foreign languages is expected in more and more workplaces, language skills are essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career you choose, if you have learned a foreign language, you will gain lifelong knowledge that brings clear benefits.
The ability to communicate directly with other nationalities automatically confers a competitive advantage on multilingual applicants.
According to a survey by YouGov, in which 4,000 adults were interviewed in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents were not well enough in any foreign language to communicate with others, and French was the only language spoken by more than 10% (15 percent) of respondents.
This is why it is important to put emphasis on children's language teaching at this time.
Speaking in several languages, especially in the language of developing countries, can be a tool in the hands of children with which they can be better able to apply for more important work as adults.
In Scotland, different languages will be dealt with in every school.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, while more will teach languages such as Mandarin and Japanese, which are expected to be of paramount importance for the UK by 2020.
Whatever the area of interest of the child, it will be able to learn several languages at independent schools and will be trained by instructors who are experts in their field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment for children that prepares and provides them with the skills they will need to succeed, whatever the future may save.
It is not difficult to see that, in the current global business environment, languages continue to be vital for a country's future, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, knowledge of modern languages should be treated as "international communication skills".
Independent schools offer young people in Scotland the possibility of choice, diversity and quality education.
Il faut bien le faire – this is how it should be.
John Edward, Chairman of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
