Harvard students are trained to rest long enough.
This year, a new class at Harvard University encouraged students to sleep more and more, fighting against the growing macho culture of caffeine-heated all-night learning.
One academic came to the conclusion that students from the world’s number one university are often completely lost when it comes to how they should care for themselves.
The course, which he believes is the first such training in the United States, was designed by Professor Charles Czeisler, who teaches sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and practices as a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
He was encouraged to develop the course by giving a lecture earlier on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came up to me and asked, ‘Why am I facing this only now as a senior?’
He said that no one ever told him about the importance of sleeping, which surprised me," he said to Telegraph.
During the course launched for the first time this year, students will be told how the right sleep patterns have a fundamental impact on their educational and sports performance, apart from having a positive impact on their general well-being.
According to Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical College and director of medical services at the university, the university decided to start the course because during the week the students were found to be extremely unsleepy.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of them, for example, they show a picture of a dorm room where students can click on coffee counters, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is influenced by sleeplessness, and why the sleeping routine is important.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the university area with interactive icons is presented to encourage participants to think about the daily routine.
“We know that we will not immediately change student behavior.
But we believe that they have the right to this knowledge – just as they have the right to be aware of the health effects of smoking," said Professor Czeisler.
A culture in which learning through a night is still flourishing, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students will lead to increasing problems of sleeplessness.
Sufficient and quality sleep is the “secret weapon” of students in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even protects them from obesity, as sleep deprivation forces the brain into starving mode and causes constant hunger.
Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, a 19-year-old student in California studying chemistry and biophysics, and last year at Harvard, she took one of the professor's first courses.
He said that the people who heard him opened his eyes and encouraged him to sword up for a university-level education.
It hopes that as a next step, postgraduate students will be able to participate in a similar training programme before they can enter the competitive sphere.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set a warning to go to bed, a wake-up call, and familiarize themselves with the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electric screens and LED light sources, which can easily dissuade them from the daily rhythm and make it difficult to fall asleep.
