What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it managed to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, the annual music event Global Citizen Festival begins in New York City. World stars will perform at the festival to stand up for a truly noble goal: the global eradication of poverty.
The Global Citizen Festival will be held for the seventh time, and it is expected that tens of thousands of people will spend the Great lawn of Central Park, where participants will not only be able to enjoy the presentation of Janet Jackson, Cardi B or Shawn Mendes, but can also draw attention to the real purpose of the event: the elimination of deep poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival was first held in 2012 as part of the Global Poverty Project. The project is run by an international stakeholder group aimed at eradicating poverty by involving more and more people in the active fight against poverty.
Free tickets (unless they refuse to pay for VIP tickets) can be awarded to those who undertake to perform certain tasks or “acts”, such as volunteering, sending emails to a leading politician, a phone call, or any other meaningful activity to draw attention to the goal of the project: eradicating poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen actually been in achieving the goals set in the last 12 years?
Is it really an effective tool to reward people with concert tickets to convince others of the importance of action, or is this just another form of so-called "clicktivism" when people feel they have contributed to a case by signing an online petition or writing a Twitter message?
Since 2011, according to Global Citizen data, more than 19 million "actions" have been carried out by project promoters for many different purposes.
According to the organisation, these actions contributed to the allocation of 37 billion dollars by world leaders to policies and commitments against poverty, which could affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group claimed 390 commitments and announcements that they came from their actions, 10 billion of which were already paid out or collected during fundraising.
The group estimates that the money collected had already had a direct impact on the lives of nearly 649 million people.
The main commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a partnership based in the United Kingdom, between investors and contractors, which aims to "help children achieve their potential." The organization promised Rwanda $35 million to help eradicate hunger after receiving over 4700 Twitter messages from "global citizens".
"With the support of the UK Government and donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can banish social injustices and malnutrition among the footnotes in the history books," said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Power of Nutrition to the crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also claims that, after more than 5,000 actions were requested by the United Kingdom to improve the food supply of mothers and their children, the government allocated resources to the Power of Nutrition project, which will improve the food supply of 5 million women and children.
One of the frequently asked questions published on the Global Citizen’s website is: “Why do you think deep poverty can be eradicated?"
According to the Global Citizen’s reply: “It will be a long and difficult journey, in which we sometimes get stuck and sometimes fail.
But like the former civil rights and anti-segregation movements, we also achieve our goal, because together we are stronger."
Among other things, Janet Jackson, Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe will be performing at this year's New York event, and the hosts will be Deborah-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
