National Trust is looking for a secret life for bats
New research is underway on a Scottish-territorial estate designed to find out how bats exploit landscape features during hunting.
Researchers hope that the results will provide new information on the behaviour of single flying mammals, which could benefit from future species conservation initiatives.
National Trust for Scotland scientists will investigate the behaviour of common and soprano dwarf bats, brown long-eared bats and water bats in Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
At the appropriate points of the area, special recording devices are installed to record bat activities during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will use manual detectors to collect mobile data.
A detailed analysis of the recordings can determine the frequency of bat sounds and what species is doing.
Researchers also provide habitat maps and reports to determine in detail how animal behaviour is shaped according to landscape.
Rob Dewar, the NTS nature conservation consultant, hopes that the results will reveal what are the most important habitats for bats and how they are used by which species.
This information helps to determine the beneficial effects of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, and how best to preserve forested areas for bats and other affected species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have decreased significantly over the last century.
Construction and land development work disturbs the animals’ sleeping areas and reduces their living space.
Wind turbines and street lighting are a risk factor for them, as are flypapers placed, certain chemical processes used for building materials, and attacks on domestic cats.
Bats aren't actually completely blind.
However, because of their predatory nature at night, they rely much more on their hearing when they hunt prey than on their sight.
They can use sophisticated techniques based on the reflection of ultrasound to determine the exact location of insects and of the terrain in their path.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76 000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
They work with ten qualified professionals who regularly conduct studies and sleep-place examinations and occasionally participate in rescue work.
The organization established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten bat trees in Scotland.
According to estate manager David Thompson, the area is an ideal habitat for bats.
“Here, in Threade, bats have a great place, ” he said.
– There are old buildings, lots of old trees, and everything else needed for a good living space.
But there's a lot we don't know about bats, and thanks to work here and in other similar areas, we can learn more about what they need to have a great time."
He also stressed the importance of ensuring that bats live there before the renovation of buildings, as destroying a single colony could result in the destruction of 400 female and young individuals, which could lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected animals, their destruction, harassment and habitat disturbance are prohibited by law.
Elisabeth Ferrell, representative of Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, also asked for the help of the population.
He said: “There is still much that we do not know about bats, and we do not have any information about the situation of the population of most domestic species.”
