Some important information about Palu and Donggala on the island of Celebes:
Palu was built at the end of a narrow bay on the western coast of the island of Celebesz, the capital of the province of central Celebes, with an estimated population of 379 800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating the 40th anniversary of its founding when the earthquake and tsunami struck it.
Donggala governorate stretches over 300 km on the northwest coast of Celebes Island.
In 2017, the population of the government, a smaller administrative region than the province, was approximately 299 200.
Central Celebese is mainly characterised by fishing and farming, especially in the coastal areas of Donggala.
Nickel mining is an important sector of the economy, but it is concentrated mainly in Morowali, on the other side of Celebes.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Response Agency, Palut and Donggala have been hit several times by a tsunami in the last 100 years.
A tsunami in 1938 killed over 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
In 1996, a tidal wave hit West Tonggala, and nine people died.
Indonesia is situated in the geologicly active Pacific Fire Ring area, which is why earthquakes are common.
Just a few of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: On 26 December a huge seaquake began on the west coast of the Aceh province of North Sumatra, which launched a tsunami reaching 14 countries, which claimed a total of 226,000 lives along the Indian Ocean coast, and more than half of the victims died in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong quakes rocked the western coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island near Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 quake shook the southern part of Java, the largest island in Indonesia, and the tsunami on its trail claimed almost 700 casualties on the south coast.
2009: A 7.6 earthquake destroyed Padang, near the capital city of West Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people lost their lives.
2010: 7.5 quake shook one of the islands of the Mentawa archipelago near Sumatra, and sometimes it caused a 10-metre tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and claimed about 300 lives.
2016: A near-surface quake reached the governorship of Aceh Pidie Jaya. The panic and destruction of his trail have brought back many memories of the terrible tsunami in 2004.
